SIMPLE: movement
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Movement
<hw>Move"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>mouvement</ets>. See <er>Move</er>, and cf. <er>Moment</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of moving in space; change of place or posture;
motion; <as>as, the <ex>movement</ex> of an army in marching or
maneuvering; the <ex>movement</ex> of a wheel or a
machine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manner or style of moving; <as>as, a slow, or quick,
or sudden, <ex>movement</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Transference, by any means, from one situation to
another; a change of situation; progress toward a goal; advancement;
<as>as, after months of fruitless discussion there was finally some
<ex>movement</ex> toward an agreement</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Motion of the mind or feelings; emotion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The rhythmical
progression, pace, and tempo of a piece.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Any change of time
is a change of <xex>movement</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Busby.</au> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>One of the several strains or pieces, each complete in itself, with
its own time and rhythm, which make up a larger work; <as>as, the
several <ex>movements</ex> of a suite or a symphony</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A system of mechanism for
transmitting motion of a definite character, or for transforming motion;
as, the wheelwork of a watch; <as>as, a seventeen jewel
<ex>movement</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A more or less organized effort by many people to
achieve some goal, especially a social or artistic goal; <as>as, the
women's liberation <ex>movement</ex>; the progressive <ex>movement</ex>
in architecture</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Febrile movement</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>an
elevation of the body temperature; a fever.</cd> -- <col><b>Movement
cure</b></col>. <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Kinesiatrics</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Movement of the bowels</b></col>, <cd>an evacuation or stool; a
passage or discharge.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Motion.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Movement</er>,
<er>Motion</er>. <xex>Motion</xex> expresses a general idea of not being
at rest; <xex>movement</xex> is oftener used to express a definite,
regulated motion, esp. a progress.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movent</ent>⟦br⟧
